k Arrangements In Changing European Workplaces -- t13. Work Hours Mismatch In The United States And Australia -- t14. Renewed Energy For Change: Government Policies Supporting Workplace Flexibility In Australia -- t15. Flexible Employment And The Introduction Of Work-Life Balance Programs In Japan -- t16. Government Policies Supporting Workplace Flexibility: The State Of Play In Japan -- tConclusions: Solving The Workplace/Workforce Mismatch -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough today's family has changed, the workplace has not—and the resulting one-size-fits-all workplace has become profoundly mismatched to the needs of an increasingly diverse and varied workforce. As changes in the composition of the workforce exert new demands on employers, considerable attention is being paid to how workplaces can be structured more flexibly to achieve the goals of employers and employees.Workplace Flexibility brings together sixteen essays authored by leading experts in economics, demography, political science, law, sociology, anthropology, and management. Collectively, they make the case for workplace flexibility, as well as examine existing business practices and public policy regarding flexibility in the United States, Europe, Australia, and Japan. Workplace Flexibility underscores the need to realign the structure of work in time and place with the needs of the changing workforce.Considering the positive and negative consequences for employer and employee alike, the authors argue that, although there is not an easy solution to creating and implementing flexibility practices—in the United States or abroad—redesigning the workplace is essential if today's workers are effectively to meet the demands of life and work and if employers are successfully able to attract and retain top talent and improve performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFlexible work arrangementszUnited States. 0aWork and familyzUnited States. 4aBusiness (General). 4aGeneral Economics. 4aLabor History. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh1 aBeck, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBianchi, Suzanne M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, James T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourke, Juliet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampos, Belinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristensen, Kathleen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDrago, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDulk, Laura den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEby, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalinsky, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGornick, Janet C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaider, Steven J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHewlett, Sylvia Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Qinlei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchens, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIwao, Sumiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Suzan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoughran, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoen, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb